<div id="review_2859843" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2859843" />
    <a title="Sean" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/47013-sean"><img alt="Sean" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1626986273p2/47013.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2859843?book_show_action=true">Jul 09, 2007</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sean" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sean" href="/user/show/47013-sean">Sean</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780143037897" href="/book/show/386222.Slow_Man">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2859843" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2076823888933534119">I can&apos;t deny that JM Coetzee is indeed a talented writer. Clear, concise, exacting prose. And duh, he did win the Nobel Prize after all. But I don&apos;t think this one is the one read. (&quot;Disgrace&quot; probably is.) What starts out as a quite conventional story soon morphs into something bordering on ludicrous. Is it magical realism? A darkly comedic satire on death vs. consciousness? Or just a novelist indulging in not having to adhere to any chosen path or structure? And not bothering to answer some ke</span>
  <span id="freeText2076823888933534119" style="display:none">I can't deny that JM Coetzee is indeed a talented writer. Clear, concise, exacting prose. And duh, he did win the Nobel Prize after all. But I don't think this one is the one read. ("Disgrace" probably is.) What starts out as a quite conventional story soon morphs into something bordering on ludicrous. Is it magical realism? A darkly comedic satire on death vs. consciousness? Or just a novelist indulging in not having to adhere to any chosen path or structure? And not bothering to answer some key questions about certain characters? As a mediation on aging, intimacy and mortality, it excels. As a "novel", it fails to deliver a coherent narrative. And soon becomes tedious. If it weren't so short and a fast read, I probably would've tossed it aside.</span>
  <a data-text-id="2076823888933534119" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


