      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Linda Abhors the New GR Design" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Linda Abhors the New GR Design" href="/user/show/8619142-linda-abhors-the-new-gr-design">Linda Abhors the New GR Design</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780143037897" href="/book/show/386222.Slow_Man">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/8619142-linda-abhors-the-new-gr-design?shelf=1001-books-bucket-list">1001-books-bucket-list</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/8619142-linda-abhors-the-new-gr-design?shelf=primer-reto-del-2015-los-nobel">primer-reto-del-2015-los-nobel</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1148536042" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer18192714734996600904">So many have already pointed out the contradictions in this novel that I won&apos;t repeat them. Only note that in its metafictional references, it recalled Unamuno&apos;s &quot;Niebla&quot; .......but without the heavy-handed determinism. Almost as though Coetzee just couldn&apos;t bring himself to do it, to dive in head-first. While not as moving (in an ugly way) as &quot;Disgrace&quot;, it does present musings on a variety of topics: photography, authorship and ownership, aging alone, love, beauty and attraction. In two of the</span>
  <span id="freeText18192714734996600904" style="display:none">So many have already pointed out the contradictions in this novel that I won't repeat them. Only note that in its metafictional references, it recalled Unamuno's "Niebla" .......but without the heavy-handed determinism. Almost as though Coetzee just couldn't bring himself to do it, to dive in head-first. While not as moving (in an ugly way) as "Disgrace", it does present musings on a variety of topics: photography, authorship and ownership, aging alone, love, beauty and attraction. In two of the three novels by Coetzee that I've read, he has presented us with despicable, self-centred protagonists...and yet, the novels are so readable that I can't give up on them. Normally, it's hard for me to read a book if I cannot get behind the characters. But even though he is so unapologetic about it, I still finish them.</span>
  <a data-text-id="18192714734996600904" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


