<div id="review_1439310411" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1439310411" />
    <a title="Robert Wechsler" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/17447518-robert-wechsler"><img alt="Robert Wechsler" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1365431820p2/17447518.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1439310411?book_show_action=true">Nov 10, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Robert Wechsler" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Robert Wechsler" href="/user/show/17447518-robert-wechsler">Robert Wechsler</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780670034598" href="/book/show/926604.Slow_Man">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/17447518-robert-wechsler?shelf=australasian-lit">australasian-lit</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1439310411" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7041007753178944243">I fel this was far from Coetzee&apos;s best work, but its problems are inextricably bound to one of the novel’s goals, as I read it: lampooning fiction’s insistence on action. The result of this is, in the novel&apos;s second half, an appropriate dullness, but dullness all the same.<br/><br/>My principal interest was in watching Coetzee do what he felt he needed to do, despite the effect it may have on the reader. It’s great that he has the self-control to keep the novel from falling into broad humor, which would h</span>
  <span id="freeText7041007753178944243" style="display:none">I fel this was far from Coetzee's best work, but its problems are inextricably bound to one of the novel’s goals, as I read it: lampooning fiction’s insistence on action. The result of this is, in the novel's second half, an appropriate dullness, but dullness all the same.<br /><br />My principal interest was in watching Coetzee do what he felt he needed to do, despite the effect it may have on the reader. It’s great that he has the self-control to keep the novel from falling into broad humor, which would have been most writers’ approach to the material (not that this is a problem for him; broad humor is not his thing). But I think he went too far in the opposite direction.<br /><br />I enjoyed the metafictional aspects of the novel, and how Coetzee played them down. But I found even most of the philosophical discussions in this novel dull, and was also not taken with its allusory aspects. </span>
  <a data-text-id="7041007753178944243" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


