<div id="review_3667297127" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3667297127" />
    <a title="Felix" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/22327118-felix"><img alt="Felix" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1410543537p2/22327118.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3667297127?book_show_action=true">Nov 29, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Felix" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Felix" href="/user/show/22327118-felix">Felix</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/22327118-felix?shelf=south-african">south-african</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3667297127" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16362845798352027740">I&apos;ve read most of Coetzee&apos;s novels. This one is the strangest so far. This novel plays a lot with the concept of a a novel. It unfolds in layers, like a Kazuo Ishiguro story, but the author also seems to be present within the narrative, almost like in <i>Mason &amp; Dixon</i>. I&apos;m sort of grasping for points of comparison, because I&apos;ve never really read anything that tries to do what <i>Slow Man</i> tries to do.<br/><br/>This novel concerns the slow recovery of an elderly man who is the victim of a traffic collision. He re</span>
  <span id="freeText16362845798352027740" style="display:none">I've read most of Coetzee's novels. This one is the strangest so far. This novel plays a lot with the concept of a a novel. It unfolds in layers, like a Kazuo Ishiguro story, but the author also seems to be present within the narrative, almost like in <i>Mason &amp; Dixon</i>. I'm sort of grasping for points of comparison, because I've never really read anything that tries to do what <i>Slow Man</i> tries to do.<br /><br />This novel concerns the slow recovery of an elderly man who is the victim of a traffic collision. He requires home help, and a couple of different nurses come to care for him. The novel is mostly focused around the relationship between one particular nurse, Marijana, and Paul, the protagonist. But then it's also about Elizabeth Costello, because she appears in this novel too, and she often seems to be somehow <i>directing</i> events. It's quite strange. It blurs the lines between author and text. Coetzee's later novels are definitely much more experimental than his earlier work.</span>
  <a data-text-id="16362845798352027740" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


