  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3570410508" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3570410508" />
    <a title="Sumallya Mukhopadhyay" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/15523221-sumallya-mukhopadhyay"><img alt="Sumallya Mukhopadhyay" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1504877193p2/15523221.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3570410508?book_show_action=true">Sep 28, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sumallya Mukhopadhyay" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sumallya Mukhopadhyay" href="/user/show/15523221-sumallya-mukhopadhyay">Sumallya Mukhopadhyay</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3570410508" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13192983315996564299">Slow Man, Coetzee<br/><br/>Do writers, in general, suck the life out of the characters to conjure up a novel? Do they not sympathise with the characters they have created with the stroke of their pen? Do they not feel their pain?<br/><br/>I do not understand Coetzee. I do not want to. It is Elizabeth Costello, the Australian novelist who appears in&apos; Slow Man&apos;, trying to direct the path of Paul Rayment’s life, whom I want to decipher. She says that Paul Rayment has happened to her; he has appeared in some imaginativ</span>
  <span id="freeText13192983315996564299" style="display:none">Slow Man, Coetzee<br /><br />Do writers, in general, suck the life out of the characters to conjure up a novel? Do they not sympathise with the characters they have created with the stroke of their pen? Do they not feel their pain?<br /><br />I do not understand Coetzee. I do not want to. It is Elizabeth Costello, the Australian novelist who appears in' Slow Man', trying to direct the path of Paul Rayment’s life, whom I want to decipher. She says that Paul Rayment has happened to her; he has appeared in some imaginative realm of her unconscious, and, in turn, she wants to weave a story with Paul as the central character. Is it possible to separate the novel from the novelist? Do novels have an independent existence, bereft of the novelist’s shadow? Following Barthes, many will argue that the novel can exist as an independent entity. The author dies, and the reader gives a new lease of life to the novel. But the novel and the characters in themselves do not have any agential thrust. The subjective analysis and interpretation of the readers infuse the novel with new meanings. Here, in 'Slow Man', Paul Rayment, the character whom Costello follows, argues against such an observation. Paul refuses to be chained in Costello’s imagination. Though he initially acquiesces to Costello’s wishes, he soon finds his own path. Paul does not act in the manner Costello asks him to. He does not provide Costello with an intriguing, fast-paced plot. In the end, Paul does not allow Costello to be a part of his life. He simply says ‘goodbye’ to his would-be creator and continues living his life.<br /><br />If this, in my view, is the central theme of the novel, it is also about the life of Paul Rayment, the man who meets with an accident that results in an amputation of a leg. After the accident, Paul shuts himself in his flat. His truncated body makes him realise that he cannot lead a normal life. He hires Marijana to look after his daily needs and inevitably develops feelings for her. One cannot possibly say that Paul falls in love with Marijana, with whom he has things in common. For instance, their erstwhile life in Europe and their socio-cultural status as immigrants in Australia. What Paul desires is to have a family with Marijana. Childless that he is, Paul hopes to have children who will keep him alive in their thoughts. He believes that ‘each new birth a new miracle’ that happens in this world. He wants to sponsor Drago’s college fees. He rescues Ljuba when she is accused of stealing. When nothing works out, he wants to be the Godfather of Marijana’s children.<br /> <br />In his efforts to separate the character and the man, Coetzee unapologetically portrays the sixty-year old Paul as a lost, lonely soul who craves for companionship. As the novel ends, Paul fails to create an impression unlike other Coetzee characters - for example, David Lurie and Simón. I do not think 'Slow Man' is one of Coetzee’s finest works, but someone who is already familiar with Coetzee’s writings might enjoy reading the novel. <br /> <br /> <br /><br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="13192983315996564299" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

