<div id="review_2299051557" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2299051557" />
    <a title="Kristel" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1993309-kristel"><img alt="Kristel" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1569870309p2/1993309.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2299051557?book_show_action=true">Jul 20, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kristel" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kristel" href="/user/show/1993309-kristel">Kristel</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780670034598" href="/book/show/926604.Slow_Man">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1993309-kristel?shelf=1001-challenge">1001-challenge</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1993309-kristel?shelf=1001-books">1001-books</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1993309-kristel?shelf=botm2019">botm2019</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2299051557" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14234946988290974586">In this novel by Coetzee, I felt that the author was playing around a bit with experimental novel in his introduction of Elizabeth Costello as an author into this story of Paul, an older man who lost a leg in a car/bicycle accident. Coetzee is exploring the nature of care, man&apos;s desire to leave a legacy and the authors&apos; relationship with the characters. Coetzee references Beckett early on (page 141); four people in four corners being wasted like tramps in Beckett. Elizabeth Costello states that </span>
  <span id="freeText14234946988290974586" style="display:none">In this novel by Coetzee, I felt that the author was playing around a bit with experimental novel in his introduction of Elizabeth Costello as an author into this story of Paul, an older man who lost a leg in a car/bicycle accident. Coetzee is exploring the nature of care, man's desire to leave a legacy and the authors' relationship with the characters. Coetzee references Beckett early on (page 141); four people in four corners being wasted like tramps in Beckett. Elizabeth Costello states that she is being. Elizabeth Costello is a character (title) of another work by Coetzee that I read a while ago. I wished I had read them closer together. <br /><br />I thought the book started strong with the accident and how Paul, a single man in his 60s viewed his life after the accident. I always enjoy books that look at older people and their struggles. <br /><br />Quotes:<br />"These young people who have been assigned to care for them know they have nothing left to give to the tribe and there do not count."<br />"So young and yet so heartless? He cries to himself. How did I come to fall into their hands? Better for old to tend the old, the dying the dying? <br /><br />After the opening of the story then enters Elizabeth Costello, who represents the author. She is omniscience. She knows what has happened and she knows things about minor characters, etc. She represents the author. The book now takes a different turn from nature of caring/legacy and delves into the relationship the author has with his characters. I struggled more to stay engaged at this point but appreciated knowing what the authors themes were as it helped me to push on and to reflect on what and why Elizabeth Costello was in this book. We see how the author manipulates and changes his or her mind as they go on with the book. Elizabeth Costello represents the struggle that the author experiences with his characters. Rather exhausted, nye on to death, by the appearance of Mrs. Costello. Homeless when the character has no direction. <br /><br />Overall, I find the author Coetzee growing on me. I've read 4 of his novels. This one is set in Australia. Paul is French/Dutch man who had worked as a photographer though I never got the sense that he was good. He was more interested in collecting photographs as historical documents. He hoped to leave a legacy of his photographs to the library. He is an old man who never moved on in life. His choice is not to make choices and avoid change. </span>
  <a data-text-id="14234946988290974586" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

