<div id="review_1939082520" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1939082520" />
    <a title="LindaJ^" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4999879-lindaj"><img alt="LindaJ^" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1486929124p2/4999879.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1939082520?book_show_action=true">Mar 11, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="LindaJ^" class="user" itemprop="url" name="LindaJ^" href="/user/show/4999879-lindaj">LindaJ^</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780670034598" href="/book/show/926604.Slow_Man">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4999879-lindaj?shelf=over-70">over-70</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1939082520" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6918741008876295347">This book lingered on my TBR shelves for far too long. I know Coetzee has won many awards. This is one of the two books by him on my shelves and the one that has been there the longest and as I surveyed the shelf for the next book to crack, I decided its time had come. <br/><br/>The beginning, with an older man - Paul - being hit by a bicycle, made me think of <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/11797374.How_It_All_Began' title='How It All Began by Penelope Lively' rel='nofollow noopener'>How It All Began</a> where the book starts with an older woman being mugged. But not much was similar after the opening. Paul is badly mangled and he l</span>
  <span id="freeText6918741008876295347" style="display:none">This book lingered on my TBR shelves for far too long. I know Coetzee has won many awards. This is one of the two books by him on my shelves and the one that has been there the longest and as I surveyed the shelf for the next book to crack, I decided its time had come. <br /><br />The beginning, with an older man - Paul - being hit by a bicycle, made me think of <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/11797374.How_It_All_Began" title="How It All Began by Penelope Lively" rel="nofollow noopener">How It All Began</a> where the book starts with an older woman being mugged. But not much was similar after the opening. Paul is badly mangled and he loses a leg. He is not happy that his leg was amputated and refuses to consider a prostheses. Instead he goes home with his Zimmer frame, a pair of crutches, and a home care nurse who will assist him with the activities of daily life and tending for his stump. Paul needs the nurse because he has no family. He's been divorced for years and has no children. <br /><br />Paul does not like his first nurse and quickly fires her. After a few weeks of different temporary nurses, one arrives that he likes. And the more time she attends him, the more he likes her. She is a good nurse and is a Croatian immigrant to Australia. Paul learns about her family during the weeks she cares for him. He meets her youngest daughter and then her teenage son Drago. Paul decides he has fallen in love with her.<br /><br />Then, out of the blue, Elizabeth Costello shows up and doesn't leave. Costello is an author and she keeps telling Paul he is a tortoise and needs to get moving. She camps out in his house and he, perhaps foolishly, allows it. She eggs him on, trying to get him to do something interesting. But even when he does, she accuses him of being a tortoise and of being hard-hearted. It seems the author is having a lot of trouble getting her character to do what she thinks he should.<br /><br />It is an interesting book. I did not really care for the Costello intrusion and liked the book better before she appeared. However, it was quite an ingenious twist to show the reader how a writer has to struggle with a character who refuses to be written the way the writer thinks the character should be. I liked the beginning more because of how Paul, having lost a leg, wondered about what his life was worth now that he was less than whole.<br /><br />This was a 3.5 read that I rounded up to 4.</span>
  <a data-text-id="6918741008876295347" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

